-- Crude Options Volatility Declines as Futures Little Changed
-- B y   B a r b a r a   P o w e l l
-- 2013-07-23T20:09:01Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-07-23/crude-options-volatility-declines-as-futures-little-changed.html
Crude options volatility retreated
as September futures rose on the first day of trading as the
front-month contract.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
September, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a
gauge of options value, was 21.95 percent on the  New York
Mercantile Exchange  as of 3:40 p.m., down from 22.98 percent
yesterday.  West Texas Intermediate crude for September delivery rose
29 cents to settle at $107.23 a barrel on the Nymex.  The most-active options in electronic trading today were
November $75 puts, which fell 3 cents to 10 cents a barrel on
volume of 4,256 lots traded as of 3:46 p.m. September $105 puts
were the second-most active, declining 25 cents to $1.44 on
volume of 2,961 contracts.  Puts accounted for 65 percent of electronic trading volume.
In the prior session, bearish bets made up 59 percent of 235,009
contracts exchanged.  September $90 puts were the most-active options yesterday
with 24,125 contracts changing hands as they fell 5 cents to 6
cents a barrel. September $100 puts increased 4 cents to 56
cents on 15,898 lots.  Open interest was highest for December $80 puts, with
38,351 contracts. Next were December $90 puts with 37,197 lots
and December $70 puts with 35,754.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information the next business day on open-outcry volume, where the bulk of options activity occurs.  To contact the reporter on this story:
